Package fpe

Class LinkedList<T>

java.lang.Object
fpe.LinkedList<T>
Type Parameters:
T - the type of elements held by the list
public class LinkedList<T>
extends Object
Custom linked list class for the purposes of this exercise implementing a variety of convenience methods.

Implemented using an internal Node class.

Note that an empty list is represented by a list whose Node object is null, rather than a list whose Node object contains a null head and a null tail.

    • prepend

      private static <T> LinkedList.Node<T> prepend​(T item, LinkedList.Node<T> tail)
      Creates a new Node containing a given object which points to a provided tail.

      Example usage: 
           
 Node<T> numbers = new Node<>(1, 2, 3, 4, 5);
 Node<T> moreNumbers = prepend(6, numbers);
      Type Parameters:
      T - the type of element held by the node being operated on
      Parameters:
      item - the item to be prepended to the list represented by the tail node
      tail - a node representing the list to be prepended to
      Returns:
      a new Node<T> with the prepended item as its head and the given tail as its tail

    • isEmpty

      public boolean isEmpty()
      Returns whether or not this list's contents are null. Note that a LinkedList is only empty when its member node, contents, is null. A LinkedList with an initialised contents node whose head and tail are null is not considered empty.
      Returns:
      true if the list is considered empty, i.e. its contents are null

    • head

    • tail

      public LinkedList<T> tail()
      Returns a LinkedList<T> containing every element of this list except the first one. If the list is empty or doesn't have a tail, an empty list is returned.
      Returns:
      a list of every item in this list besides the first item.
